"Nicolè F., Dahlgren J.P., Vivat A., Till-Bottraud I., Ehrlén J.","Interdependent effects of habitat quality and climate on population growth of an endangered plant",2011,"Journal of Ecology","99","5",,"1211","1218",,,10.1111/j.1365-2745.2011.01852.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80051741683&partnerID=40&md5=879a02b03461afbd43f0721c213c6285","Laboratoire BVpam, Université de Lyon, Université de Saint-Etienne, F-42000 Saint-Etienne, France; Department of Botany, Stockholm University, SE-10691 Stockholm, Sweden; Pôle Natura 2000, Campana 05600 Mont Dauphin, France; Laboratoire d'Ecologie Alpine, Université Joseph Fourier, 38041 Grenoble, France","Nicolè, F., Laboratoire BVpam, Université de Lyon, Université de Saint-Etienne, F-42000 Saint-Etienne, France; Dahlgren, J.P., Department of Botany, Stockholm University, SE-10691 Stockholm, Sweden; Vivat, A., Pôle Natura 2000, Campana 05600 Mont Dauphin, France; Till-Bottraud, I., Laboratoire d'Ecologie Alpine, Université Joseph Fourier, 38041 Grenoble, France; Ehrlén, J., Department of Botany, Stockholm University, SE-10691 Stockholm, Sweden","1.To predict the viability of populations, it is essential to clarify how performance depends both on large-scale environmental changes, such as climate warming, and on the local habitat. However, in spite of their potential importance, effects of interactions between large-scale environmental changes and the local environment on population viability have rarely been examined. 2.We investigated how population dynamics of the endangered alpine plant Dracocephalum austriacum depend on local habitat quality and climatic variation, as well as how effects of climate depend on local habitat. We used lasso regression shrinkage and integral projection models to identify effects on vital rates and population growth rates in seven populations over seven annual transitions. 3.Populations on steeper slopes had lower survival and stochastic population growth rate than populations on more gentle slopes. In years with low spring temperatures and high summer temperatures, survival and population growth rate were lower. In addition, the negative effects of high summer temperatures did depend on local habitat quality, being more negative in populations on steeper slopes. 4.Combining the net positive effects of high spring temperature and the net negative effects of high summer temperature on plant vital rates with predicted climate change over the next 30years suggested that effects on D. austriacum would be relatively small. 5.Synthesis. Our results show that different aspects of a warmer climate may have opposing effects on populations, and that climatic effects may depend on local habitat quality. Such interactive effects should be accounted for when determining effects of large-scale environmental changes on population and community dynamics. © 2011 The Authors. Journal of Ecology © 2011 British Ecological Society.","Climate change; Dracocephalum austriacum; Global warming; Integral projection model; Local environment; Plant population and community dynamics; Slope; Spatio-temporal variation; Temperature","alpine environment; climate change; climate effect; dicotyledon; endangered species; growth rate; habitat quality; population growth; population viability analysis; spatial variation; survival; temperature effect; temporal variation; Dracocephalum",,,,,,"Åberg, P., Size-based demography of the seaweed Ascophyllum nodosum in stochastic environments (1992) Ecology, 73, pp. 1488-1501; Alvarez-Buylla, E.R., Density dependence and patch dynamics in tropical rain forests: matrix models and applications to a tree species (1994) The American Naturalist, 143, pp. 155-191; Bensettiti, F., Gaudillat, V., Malengreau, D., Quéré, E., (2002) Cahiers d'habitats Natura 2000. Connaissance et gestion des habitats et des espèces d'intérêt communautaire. Tome 6: Espèces végétales, , La Documentation Française, Paris, France; Bonin, A., Nicole, F., Pompanon, F.C.O., Miaud, C., Taberlet, P., Population adaptive index: a new method to help measure intraspecific genetic diversity and prioritize populations for conservation (2007) Conservation Biology, 21, pp. 697-708; Dahlgren, J.P., Alternative regression methods are not considered in Murtaugh (2009) or by ecologists in general (2010) Ecology Letters, 13, pp. E7-E9; Dahlgren, J.P., Ehrlén, J., Linking environmental variation to population dynamics of a forest herb (2009) Journal of Ecology, 97, pp. 666-674; Davison, R., Jacquemyn, H., Adriaens, D., Honnay, O., de Kroon, H., Tuljapurkar, S., Demographic effects of extreme weather events on a short-lived calcareous grassland species: stochastic life table response experiments (2010) Journal of Ecology, 98, pp. 255-267; Doak, D.F., Morris, W.F., Demographic compensation and tipping points in climate-induced range shifts (2010) Nature, 7318, pp. 959-962; Dullinger, S., Dirnböck, T., Grabherr, G., Modelling climate change-driven treeline shifts: relative effects of temperature increase, dispersal and invasibility (2004) Ecology, 92, pp. 241-252; Easterling, M.R., Ellner, S.P., Dixon, P.M., Size-specific sensitivity: applying a new structured population model (2000) Ecology, 81, pp. 694-708; Ellner, S.P., Rees, M., Integral projection models for species with complex demography (2006) The American Naturalist, 167, pp. 410-428; Fieberg, J., Ellner, S.P., Stochastic matrix models for conservation and management: a comparative review of methods (2001) Ecology Letters, 4, pp. 244-266; Freville, H., Colas, B., Riba, M., Caswell, H., Mignot, A., Imbert, E., Olivieri, I., Spatial and temporal demographic variability in the endemic plant species Centaurea corymbosa (Asteraceae) (2004) Ecology, 85, pp. 694-703; Gotelli, N.J., Ellison, A.M., Forecasting extinction risk with nonstationary matrix models (2006) Ecological Applications, 16, pp. 51-61; Harrell, F.E., (2001) Regression Modeling Strategies, , Springer-Verlag, New York, NY, USA